The domain of the complex logarithm of (s+a)/(s+b) is the set of all non-zero complex numbers in the complex plane such that (s+a)/(s+b) is not purely real and negative. Specifically, we require that (s+a)/(s+b) has the same sign as its real part, so that the complex logarithm of (s+a)/(s+b) is well-defined. Thus, the domain is given by:

Domain of complex logarithm of (s+a)/(s+b) = { s ∈ ℂ | (s+a)/(s+b) ≠ 0, Re[(s+a)/(s+b)] >0}

In addition, since the complex logarithm is a multi-valued function, the domain may need to be further specified depending on precisely how we choose a branch of the logarithm. Specifically, the domain may need to be restricted to avoid branch cuts, which are the discontinuities in the value of the logarithm due to the multi-valuedness of the function.

function [density, known] = alloy(unknown)

    % Input values - no need to assign to a variable, given as 'unknown'
    % unknown = [2 3 4 638; 3 3 4 710; 5 2 3 706];

    % Setting up the system of equations
    A = [2 3 4; 3 3 4; 5 2 3];
    B = [638; 710; 706];

    % Solving the system of equations for the densities
    density = A\B;

    % Computing the mass of each metal in the input alloys (volume x density)
    mass = [A(:,1)*density(1), A(:,2)*density(2), A(:,3)*density(3)];

    % Computing the weight percentage of each metal in the input alloys
    weight_percentage = (mass ./ sum(mass, 2)) * 100;

    % Storing the results in the cell array 'known'
