In UE5 GAS, the best way to differentiate between a single target skill and an AOE skill in the ground actor is to use a combination of Gameplay Tags and different Ability class implementations. Here's how you can achieve this:

1. Create Gameplay Tags: Add specific tags that categorize your abilities based on their targeting types. For example, create tags like `"Ability.Targeting.SingleTarget"` and `"Ability.Targeting.AOE"`.

2. Assign Tags to Abilities: In your Ability classes (both single target and AOE), assign the appropriate Gameplay Tags according to their targeting type. This will make it easier to identify the type of ability in the ground actor later.

3. Create a Base Target Ability class: Create a base target ability class that derives from `UGameplayAbility`, which will be responsible for common functionality shared by both single target and AOE abilities. This can include spawning and updating the ground target indicator, location validation, etc.

4. Create Single Target and AOE Ability classes: From the base target ability class, create two subclasses—one for Single Target abilities and another for AOE abilities. Each subclass will handle its unique targeting logic, decide valid targets, and apply the appropriate effects.

5. Check Gameplay Tags and use the correct Ability class: When activating an ability, based on the associated Gameplay Tags, decide whether to use a single target ability class or an AOE ability class instance. You can check the tags in the ground actor or whichever part of your game logic is responsible for activating the abilities.

```cpp
// Example method to activate an ability based on the Gameplay Tag
void AMyCharacter::ActivateAbilityByTag(const FGameplayTag& AbilityTag)
{
	UGameplayAbility* AbilityToActivate = nullptr;

	if (AbilityTag == FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(FName("Ability.Targeting.SingleTarget")))
	{
		AbilityToActivate = NewObject<USingleTargetAbility>();
		// Make sure to set the Ability Info, Level, and Context
	}
	else if (AbilityTag == FGameplayTag::RequestGameplayTag(FName("Ability.Targeting.AOE")))
	{
		AbilityToActivate = NewObject<UAOEAbility>();
		// Make sure to set the Ability Info, Level, and Context
	}

	// Activate the ability if it's not null
